chatgpt_double_star.new_statement: Government should ensure that every resident can enroll in a dependable, nationwide basic plan covering primary, preventive, mental health, and emergency care, with strong protection against catastrophic bills. Beyond that floor, people and employers should be free to choose among regulated private and supplemental options, so competition and innovation can improve service and responsiveness. To keep the system sustainable, policy should focus on simpler enrollment, fair price setting tied to outcomes, anti-fraud enforcement, and investments in underserved communities and rural providers.

chatgpt_double_star_rankings.new_statement: Government should guarantee a universal, affordable baseline of essential care—especially preventive, primary, mental-health, and emergency services—and protect everyone from catastrophic medical bills, while preserving patient choice and allowing private supplemental coverage and innovation. To keep costs and quality in check, it should set clear standards, negotiate or benchmark fair prices, and require transparent billing, with targeted subsidies and simple, portable enrollment so coverage follows people across jobs and life changes. Phased implementation, strong anti-fraud oversight, and support for rural and community providers can improve access and outcomes while maintaining fiscal responsibility.

chatgpt_double_star_personas.new_statement: Government should guarantee that every person can get essential care—primary, preventive, mental health, and emergency services—and be protected from catastrophic medical bills, regardless of job status or income. People who want additional options should be able to choose private or employer-sponsored plans on top of that baseline, with clear rules that prevent discrimination for preexisting conditions. To keep the system affordable, government should set transparent standards, negotiate or benchmark fair prices, reduce waste and fraud, and invest in local clinics and rural providers with simple, portable enrollment.
